insert into blog_posts (title, slug, body, excerpt, category, meta_title, meta_description, linked_companies, status, published_at)
values (
  $kd$Choosing Commercial Cooking Equipment: Ranges, Ovens and Fryers$kd$,
  $kd$choosing-commercial-cooking-equipment-ranges-ovens-fryers$kd$,
  $kd$The cooking line is the heart of any commercial kitchen. Ranges, ovens and fryers do the heaviest work, draw the most utilities, and are the hardest pieces to replace once they are installed. Getting these decisions right at the start saves money, space, and a lot of operational headaches later. This guide walks through the core choices so you can match equipment to your menu, your kitchen layout, and your local code requirements.

## Gas vs electric: the first decision

Almost every cooking equipment choice starts with the fuel question. Both gas and electric have real trade-offs, and the right answer depends on your building and your menu.

Gas equipment offers instant, visible heat and fast recovery, which is why many high-volume kitchens prefer it for ranges and fryers. It depends on a gas line of adequate capacity and proper venting, so a building without existing gas service may face significant infrastructure costs.

Electric equipment tends to heat more evenly, is often easier to clean, and can be simpler to install where gas is not already run. Induction ranges in particular are efficient and keep the kitchen cooler, though they require compatible cookware. Electric units rely on having enough electrical capacity at the panel, so confirm your service before committing.

A quick way to decide: if your space already has strong gas service and your menu leans on searing, wok work, or high-volume frying, gas is usually the natural fit. If gas is absent or limited, or you want a cooler, lower-maintenance line, electric and induction deserve a serious look.

## Ranges: sizing to your menu

A range is rarely just a range. Most commercial ranges combine open burners, a flat griddle or charbroiler, and an oven base. The right configuration follows directly from what you actually cook.

- **Open burners** suit sauces, stocks, sautéing, and anything in a pot or pan.
- **Griddles** handle breakfast service, burgers, and high-volume flat-top items.
- **Charbroilers** deliver the grill marks and char flavour for proteins and vegetables.

Count the simultaneous cooking tasks at your busiest service, not your average one. A line that is fine at lunch can bottleneck during a dinner rush if you sized for the wrong peak. Leave room to grow, but avoid buying burners that sit cold all day, since they still cost money to buy, vent, and maintain.

## Ovens: convection, combi, and beyond

Ovens span a wide range of types, and the names matter.

**Convection ovens** circulate hot air with a fan for even baking and roasting. They are a reliable workhorse for most kitchens and bakeries.

**Combi ovens** combine convection heat with steam, giving you dry heat, moist heat, or a blend. They can roast, steam, braise, bake, and hold, often replacing several pieces of equipment. Combi units cost more upfront and need water and drainage, but for menus with varied cooking methods they can be the most flexible single purchase you make.

**Deck and conveyor ovens** serve specific needs such as pizza and high-throughput baking. If your concept centres on one product, a purpose-built oven usually beats a general one.

Match capacity to pan sizes and batch volume. Think in terms of how many trays you need out at once during peak, and confirm the oven accepts the pan format your recipes use.

## Fryers: capacity, recovery, and oil management

Fryers look simple but reward careful selection. The two numbers that matter most are oil capacity (how much you can cook at once) and recovery time (how fast the oil returns to temperature after food goes in). Slow recovery means greasy, undercooked results during a rush.

Consider how many fry baskets you run at peak, whether you need dedicated fryers for allergen separation, and how you will filter and dispose of oil. Built-in filtration saves labour and extends oil life. As with ranges, gas fryers recover quickly while electric fryers can be easier to site where gas is unavailable.

## Certifications, venting, and code

Commercial cooking equipment in Canada should carry recognized safety certification, and your municipality will expect it during inspection. Just as important is the ventilation and fire suppression system over the cooking line, which is governed by local code and must be sized to the equipment beneath it.

Do not treat venting as an afterthought. The hood, make-up air, and fire suppression often cost as much attention as the equipment itself, and they directly affect what you are allowed to install. Bring your equipment list to your designer and your local authority early.

## Getting design and sourcing help

Spec'ing a full cooking line is where good advice pays off. A supplier that offers design and technical drawings can lay out the line, confirm utility loads, and flag venting requirements before you buy. **Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply** and **Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment** both provide design and technical drawing services, and Russell Hendrix also offers installation. For equipment consulting and procurement, **Shop at Stop**, **Russell Hendrix**, **Nella Cutlery & Food Equipment**, and **Canada Food Equipment Ltd** are all options worth comparing. If budget is a concern, note that Shop at Stop offers equipment financing and leasing to spread the cost of a major line build.

## Where to find suppliers in Ontario

When you are ready to source ranges, ovens, and fryers, compare a few suppliers on service range, consulting depth, and lead times rather than price alone. Browse the directory's commercial equipment procurement and equipment consulting categories to see how Ontario suppliers stack up, starting with the top-ranked **Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply** and including **Russell Hendrix**, **Nella Cutlery**, and **Canada Food Equipment**. Get a quote from two or three before you commit, and ask each to walk you through utilities, venting, and warranty so there are no surprises on inspection day.$kd$,
  $kd$A practical buyer's guide to commercial ranges, ovens and fryers: gas vs electric, combi ovens, sizing to your menu, certifications, and where to get help.$kd$,
  $kd$Buying Guides$kd$,
  $kd$Commercial Ranges, Ovens and Fryers: Buyer Guide$kd$,
  $kd$How to choose commercial ranges, ovens and fryers in Ontario. Gas vs electric, combi ovens, menu sizing, certifications, and sourcing help.$kd$,
