insert into blog_posts (title, slug, body, excerpt, category, meta_title, meta_description, linked_companies, status, published_at)
values (
  $kd$Commercial Kitchen Design and Layout: A Planning Guide$kd$,
  $kd$commercial-kitchen-design-and-layout-guide$kd$,
  $kd$A commercial kitchen layout shapes every shift that follows. Get the flow right and your line moves quickly, your staff stay safe, and your equipment lasts. Get it wrong and you pay for it daily in wasted steps, bottlenecks, and failed inspections. This guide walks through how to plan a layout the right way, from workflow zones to ventilation, technical drawings, and choosing a partner who can do the drawings and supply the equipment.

## Start with the workflow, not the equipment

The most common planning mistake is shopping for equipment before mapping how food moves through the space. Design the workflow first, then place equipment to support it.

Think in zones. A typical commercial kitchen breaks into a handful of functional areas:

- **Receiving and storage**: where deliveries arrive, plus dry storage, refrigeration, and freezer space.
- **Prep**: counters, sinks, and prep tables where raw ingredients are washed, cut, and portioned.
- **Cooking line**: ranges, fryers, ovens, griddles, and the ventilation hood above them.
- **Plating and pass**: the handoff point between kitchen and service.
- **Warewashing**: dish pits, sinks, and drying racks, kept away from clean food zones.

Arrange these zones so food travels in one direction, from receiving toward the pass, without crossing back over itself. This is the principle behind both assembly-line layouts (good for high-volume, repetitive menus) and zone or island layouts (good for varied menus and larger teams). Crossing paths between raw and cooked food, or between dirty dishes and clean prep, is how contamination and collisions happen.

### Plan for the people, not just the food

Walk the route a line cook takes during a rush. Count the steps. If they pivot constantly between a fridge, a range, and a prep table that are all spread apart, the layout is fighting them. Keep frequently paired stations close, leave enough aisle width for two people to pass with hot pans, and make sure doors swing where they will not clip someone carrying a tray.

## Code and ventilation basics

In Ontario, a commercial kitchen has to satisfy several overlapping requirements: the Ontario Building Code, the Ontario Fire Code, local public health regulations enforced by your municipality, and electrical and gas safety standards. Rules and approvals vary by municipality and by project, so confirm specifics with your local authority and a qualified professional rather than assuming.

A few areas almost always come up:

- **Ventilation and hoods**: cooking equipment that produces grease-laden vapour needs a commercial hood with proper exhaust and, in most cases, make-up air to replace what gets pulled out. Hood sizing depends on the equipment underneath it, so the layout and the ventilation plan have to be designed together, not separately.
- **Fire suppression**: hood systems are typically tied to a suppression system. This needs to be coordinated early because it affects where cooking equipment can sit.
- **Plumbing and drainage**: handwashing sinks, prep sinks, warewashing, and floor drains all have placement and separation rules.
- **Grease management**: grease interceptors or traps are commonly required and take up space you need to plan for.

The takeaway: ventilation, plumbing, and fire safety are not afterthoughts you bolt on at the end. They drive where equipment can physically go, which is exactly why they belong in the earliest version of your plan.

## Technical drawings are the deliverable

A good plan becomes a set of technical drawings: scaled floor plans, equipment schedules, and elevations that show exactly what goes where, how big it is, and how it connects to power, gas, water, and exhaust. These drawings are what your contractor builds from, what inspectors review, and what keeps your equipment order accurate.

Drawings do a few things at once. They catch conflicts on paper, where fixing them is cheap, instead of on site, where it is expensive. They give every trade a single source of truth. And they let you confirm that the equipment you are about to buy actually fits the space and the utilities available.

If you are weighing models, capacities, or whether a piece fits a given footprint, treat that as part of the drawing stage. Real numbers vary by model, so get a quote and confirm dimensions against the plan before ordering.

## Using a design and equipment partner

You can hire a kitchen designer and an equipment supplier separately, but there is real value in a partner who does both. When the same team draws the plan and supplies the equipment, the drawings reflect equipment that is actually available and correctly specced, and there is no gap between what was designed and what shows up on the truck.

Two suppliers in this directory offer Design and Technical Drawings alongside equipment supply:

- **[Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply](/companies/shop-at-stop)** is the top-ranked supplier in our listings and offers the widest service range, including Design and Technical Drawings, Equipment Consulting, Commercial Equipment Procurement, and account management. For operators who want planning, specification, and supply handled by one team, it is a strong starting point.
- **[Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment](/companies/russell-hendrix)** also offers Design and Technical Drawings, plus Installation Services, which is useful if you want the same partner to plan, supply, and physically install the line.

For equipment sourcing and second opinions on specification, **[Nella Cutlery and Food Equipment](/companies/nella-cutlery)** and **[Canada Food Equipment Ltd](/companies/canada-food-equipment)** both provide Commercial Equipment Procurement and Equipment Consulting, which can help once your zones and drawings are settled and you are pricing out the build.

### Questions to ask a design partner

- Can you produce scaled drawings and an equipment schedule, not just a sketch?
- Will the plan coordinate ventilation, plumbing, and fire suppression?
- Does the equipment you spec match what you can actually supply and service?
- Can you confirm dimensions and utility requirements before I commit to an order?

## Where to find suppliers in Ontario

If you are planning a new build or a renovation, start with suppliers who can produce real technical drawings and back them with equipment supply. In this directory, Shop at Stop and Russell Hendrix both list Design and Technical Drawings, while Nella Cutlery and Canada Food Equipment round out your options for procurement and consulting. Browse the Design and Technical Drawings and Equipment Consulting categories to compare suppliers, then request quotes once your workflow zones and drawings are in hand.$kd$,
  $kd$How to plan a commercial kitchen layout: workflow zones, code and ventilation basics, technical drawings, and choosing a design partner in Ontario.$kd$,
  $kd$Buying Guides$kd$,
  $kd$Commercial Kitchen Design and Layout Guide$kd$,
  $kd$Plan a commercial kitchen the right way: workflow zones, ventilation and code basics, technical drawings, and how to pick a design partner in Ontario.$kd$,
  ARRAY['b68c7c8c-410a-4dca-95bb-350465060c10','806c39a5-e8ef-44bb-b3d8-538253aef2e5','7edb910c-02fe-404e-ba58-68828e6b131f','a5ebbe5f-713b-421c-9161-446671587c84']::uuid[], 'published', now()
)
