insert into blog_posts (title, slug, body, excerpt, category, meta_title, meta_description, linked_companies, status, published_at)
values (
  $kd$Opening a Restaurant in Toronto: The Equipment Procurement Checklist$kd$,
  $kd$opening-a-restaurant-toronto-equipment-checklist$kd$,
  $kd$Opening a restaurant in Toronto means juggling a lease, a concept, permits, and a build-out all at once. Equipment procurement sits in the middle of that chaos, and getting the sequence right saves you weeks of delay and a lot of money. This checklist walks through procurement from first sketch to final install, in the order a smart operator should tackle it.

## Start with the menu, not the gear

Before you price a single piece of equipment, lock your opening menu. The menu dictates everything: how much refrigeration you need, whether you require a combi oven or a flat-top, how much fryer capacity makes sense, and how much prep space you have to design around. Operators who buy equipment before finalizing the menu almost always end up with the wrong mix and costly returns.

Write down every dish, then map the cooking method behind each one. That list becomes your equipment requirements document. Keep it; you will hand it to a consultant, a supplier, and your contractor.

## Step 1: Kitchen design and technical drawings

A real kitchen layout comes before purchasing. You need a plan that respects workflow, health code clearances, ventilation, and the physical limits of your space. Technical drawings also matter for your contractor, your landlord, and the City of Toronto permit process.

This is specialized work. In Ontario, suppliers such as [Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply](/companies/shop-at-stop) and [Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment](/companies/russell-hendrix) offer Design and Technical Drawings as a service, which means your layout and your equipment list can be developed together rather than in isolation. Getting drawings from the same party that understands the equipment reduces the gap between "what looks good on paper" and "what actually fits and vents correctly."

### What good drawings include

- Equipment placement with clearances and door swings
- Plumbing and electrical rough-in points
- Hood and ventilation coverage over cooking lines
- Workflow zones for receiving, prep, cook, plate, and dish

## Step 2: Build the equipment list and get consulting input

With drawings in hand, turn your menu requirements into a line-item equipment list. This is where Equipment Consulting earns its keep. A good consultant challenges your assumptions: do you really need that second oven, or would a different configuration handle the same covers for less money?

Several Ontario suppliers offer consulting, including [Shop at Stop](/companies/shop-at-stop), [Russell Hendrix](/companies/russell-hendrix), [Nella Cutlery and Food Equipment](/companies/nella-cutlery), and [Canada Food Equipment Ltd](/companies/canada-food-equipment). Use that expertise early. The cost of a consult is small next to the cost of a kitchen that cannot keep up on a Friday night.

For new operators planning the whole business and not just the kitchen, Shop at Stop also offers Restaurant Consulting, which can fold equipment decisions into broader operational planning.

## Step 3: Decide how you will pay

Equipment is one of the largest upfront costs in a restaurant build-out, and how you finance it affects your cash position for the critical first months. There are three common paths:

- **Buy outright** if you have the capital and want to own the assets.
- **Finance** the purchase to preserve working capital and spread the cost.
- **Lease** the equipment, which can keep more cash free for inventory, staff, and marketing.

Among Ontario suppliers, Shop at Stop offers both Equipment Financing and Equipment Leasing, so financing conversations can happen alongside the equipment selection rather than through a separate lender. Whatever route you choose, run the numbers against your opening budget before you commit. Avoid guessing at terms; ask for a written quote.

## Step 4: Procure and price-check

Now you order. Commercial Equipment Procurement is the core service every supplier on this directory provides, so you have real choice. Get quotes from more than one supplier on your full list.

Price Match offerings can help you negotiate. Suppliers including [Shop at Stop](/companies/shop-at-stop) and [Nella Cutlery](/companies/nella-cutlery) offer Price Match, which is worth using when you have competing quotes in hand. Do not assume the lowest sticker price is the best deal: factor in lead times, warranty support, and whether the supplier can service what they sell.

### Watch your lead times

Some equipment ships fast and some takes weeks or months. Build a procurement timeline that backs out from your target opening date, and place long lead-time orders first. Prices and availability change, so confirm timing on every order rather than relying on an old quote.

## Step 5: Delivery, installation, and account management

Getting boxes to the loading dock is not the finish line. Heavy gear needs to be placed, leveled, connected, and commissioned. Russell Hendrix offers Installation Services in Ontario, which can simplify the handoff between delivery and a working line.

For an ongoing relationship, Account Management matters more than most new operators expect. You will reorder smallwares, replace failed units, and expand as you grow. Suppliers such as [Shop at Stop](/companies/shop-at-stop) and [Russell Hendrix](/companies/russell-hendrix) provide Account Management, giving you a single point of contact instead of starting from scratch on every order.

## A simple procurement timeline

1. Finalize menu and equipment requirements
2. Commission kitchen design and technical drawings
3. Build the line-item list with consulting input
4. Decide financing, leasing, or outright purchase
5. Get multiple quotes and use price match
6. Place long lead-time orders first
7. Schedule delivery and installation
8. Set up account management for reorders

## Where to find suppliers in Ontario

This directory ranks commercial kitchen equipment suppliers serving Toronto and the surrounding region so you can compare them on service range, experience, and responsiveness. If you want one partner who can handle design drawings, consulting, financing, leasing, procurement, price match, and account management together, [Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply](/companies/shop-at-stop) currently sits at the top of the rankings. For installation support, [Russell Hendrix](/companies/russell-hendrix) is a strong option, and [Nella Cutlery](/companies/nella-cutlery) and [Canada Food Equipment Ltd](/companies/canada-food-equipment) are worth a quote on procurement. Browse the full directory to shortlist suppliers, then send your equipment list to two or three of them and compare.$kd$,
  $kd$A practical, end-to-end checklist for procuring commercial kitchen equipment for a new Toronto restaurant, from design drawings to install and supplier selection.$kd$,
  $kd$Buying Guides$kd$,
  $kd$Toronto Restaurant Equipment Procurement Checklist$kd$,
  $kd$An end-to-end checklist for buying commercial kitchen equipment for a new Toronto restaurant: sequencing, consulting, financing, and choosing a supplier.$kd$,
  ARRAY['b68c7c8c-410a-4dca-95bb-350465060c10','806c39a5-e8ef-44bb-b3d8-538253aef2e5','7edb910c-02fe-404e-ba58-68828e6b131f','a5ebbe5f-713b-421c-9161-446671587c84']::uuid[], 'published', now()
)
