update service_categories set description = $kd$Account management gives a commercial kitchen a single point of contact who knows your equipment history, ordering patterns, and budget cycles. Instead of starting from scratch with every purchase, you work with a dedicated rep who can speed up quotes, track warranties, and coordinate repeat orders across multiple locations. For multi-unit operators and growing restaurant groups, this continuity often matters more than the price on any single line item. A few suppliers in this directory build their relationship model around assigned account reps rather than transactional, one-off sales.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"What does a dedicated account manager actually do for a restaurant?","answer":"A dedicated account manager acts as your single contact across quoting, ordering, and follow-up. They keep a record of what you have bought, flag warranty windows, expedite reorders of consumables and parts, and coordinate larger projects so you are not re-explaining your setup to a new person each time. The practical benefit is faster turnaround and fewer ordering mistakes."},{"question":"Is account management worth it for a single location, or only for chains?","answer":"Multi-location groups gain the most because an account manager can standardize equipment across sites and consolidate ordering. That said, even a single busy kitchen benefits when a rep already knows your floor plan, your preferred brands, and your service categories, which shortens the path from question to quote. It comes down to how often you reorder and how complex your equipment list is."},{"question":"Which suppliers in this directory offer account management?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply and Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment both list account management among their services. Shop at Stop carries the widest overall service range in the directory, which can make it convenient when you want account support bundled with procurement, consulting, and financing under one relationship."},{"question":"Does account management cost extra?","answer":"Pricing models vary by supplier and are usually tied to your overall purchasing relationship rather than billed as a separate line item. Because the structure differs from one supplier to the next, the accurate move is to ask each candidate directly how their account program works and what, if anything, it adds to your costs. Get it in writing before you commit."},{"question":"How do I switch account managers or suppliers without losing my equipment history?","answer":"Before switching, ask your current supplier for records of past purchases, model numbers, and warranty documentation. A good incoming account manager will rebuild your profile from that information so future orders and service calls reference the right equipment. Keeping your own simple inventory list also protects you regardless of which supplier you use."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$account-management$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Commercial equipment procurement covers sourcing, quoting, and supplying the core gear a kitchen runs on, from ranges and ovens to refrigeration, prep stations, and smallwares. A strong procurement partner helps you match the right model to your menu, volume, and space rather than just selling whatever is in stock. Because this is the foundational service, every supplier in this directory offers it, which means your decision usually rests on range, lead times, support, and total value. This page lists Ontario suppliers ranked on those factors.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"What should I look for when choosing an equipment procurement partner?","answer":"Look at breadth of brands carried, the supplier's willingness to spec equipment to your actual menu and volume, realistic lead times, and what happens after delivery if something fails. A partner who asks about your throughput and kitchen layout before quoting usually delivers better-fitting equipment than one who only quotes the cheapest available unit."},{"question":"Should I buy new or consider used commercial equipment?","answer":"New equipment carries full manufacturer warranties and predictable service, while used gear can lower upfront cost but adds risk on remaining lifespan and parts availability. The right call depends on the category: high-use cooking and refrigeration are often safer new, while some prep and storage items can be reasonable used. Ask the supplier about warranty and parts support either way."},{"question":"Which suppliers handle commercial equipment procurement in Ontario?","answer":"Every supplier in this directory offers procurement, including Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply, Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment, Nella Cutlery and Food Equipment, Canada Food Equipment, Chefco, W.D. Colledge, and Igloo Food Equipment. Shop at Stop ranks highest overall and lists the broadest service range, so it is a common starting point when you want procurement alongside design, financing, and consulting."},{"question":"How far ahead should I order equipment for a new build or renovation?","answer":"Order as early as your floor plan and utilities are confirmed, since some equipment carries longer lead times than others and delays can stall an entire opening. Rather than assume a fixed timeline, ask each supplier for current lead times on your specific models and build buffer into your schedule. Coordinating procurement with any design and installation work keeps everything aligned."},{"question":"Can one supplier handle my entire equipment list?","answer":"Often yes. Many suppliers can source a full kitchen so you have one quote, one delivery coordination point, and one contact for issues. Consolidating with a single procurement partner simplifies accountability, though you should still confirm they can actually supply every category you need rather than substituting unfamiliar brands."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$commercial-equipment-procurement$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Design and technical drawings translate your menu and space into a workable kitchen layout, complete with equipment placement, workflow paths, and the dimensioned plans contractors and inspectors need. Good drawings catch problems on paper, like a hood that does not fit or a cooking line that forces awkward movement, before they become expensive on-site fixes. This service is especially valuable for new builds, renovations, and any project that has to pass code and coordinate trades. Only select suppliers in this directory provide layout and technical drawing support.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"Why do I need technical kitchen drawings instead of just placing equipment myself?","answer":"Technical drawings account for ventilation, utility connections, clearances, and workflow that are easy to misjudge by eye. They give your contractor, electrician, plumber, and inspector a single coordinated reference, which reduces costly change orders mid-build. Even an experienced operator benefits from a plan that proves everything fits and meets code before anyone starts construction."},{"question":"Which suppliers in the directory offer design and technical drawings?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply and Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment both provide design and technical drawing services. If you want the drawings to flow directly into procurement and, in the case of Russell Hendrix, installation, working with a supplier that offers those services together can keep the project coordinated under fewer contacts."},{"question":"When in a project should design and drawings happen?","answer":"As early as possible, ideally before you finalize equipment purchases or sign a construction schedule. Layout decisions drive what equipment you buy, where utilities run, and how the build sequences, so getting drawings done first prevents reordering or relocating gear later. Starting late tends to create rework that costs more than the design service itself."},{"question":"Will the drawings help my kitchen pass inspection?","answer":"Proper technical drawings are built to reflect clearances, ventilation, and equipment specifications that inspectors check, which makes the approval process smoother. They are not a substitute for the inspection itself, and local requirements still apply, so confirm with your supplier and your jurisdiction that the plans address the codes relevant to your municipality."},{"question":"Do I have to buy equipment from the supplier who does my drawings?","answer":"Policies vary by supplier, so ask up front whether design support is tied to a purchase or offered as a standalone service. In practice, having the same supplier handle both design and procurement keeps specifications consistent and reduces the chance of ordering a model that does not match the plan. Clarify the arrangement before work begins."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$design-and-technical-drawings$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Equipment consulting helps you decide what to buy and why, matching machines to your menu, volume, staffing, and budget instead of guessing. A consultant can steer you away from over-buying capacity you will not use or under-buying gear that bottlenecks service during a rush. This is useful for first-time operators, concept changes, and expansions where the wrong equipment choice is expensive to undo. Several suppliers in this directory pair consulting with their procurement so advice connects directly to what they can supply.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"How is equipment consulting different from just asking a salesperson?","answer":"Consulting starts with your operation, your menu, covers, peak volume, kitchen size, and staffing, then recommends equipment that fits, rather than starting with a product to sell. The goal is the right capacity and workflow for your specific kitchen. A consultative supplier asks more questions before quoting, which usually leads to fewer regrets after the equipment arrives."},{"question":"Which suppliers in the directory offer equipment consulting?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply, Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment, Nella Cutlery and Food Equipment, Canada Food Equipment, and W.D. Colledge all list equipment consulting. Shop at Stop ranks first overall and offers the widest service range, so its consulting can connect directly to design, financing, and procurement when you want one coordinated path."},{"question":"What information should I bring to an equipment consultation?","answer":"Bring your menu or concept, expected covers or daily volume, your kitchen dimensions or floor plan, your budget range, and any existing equipment you plan to keep. The more concrete you are about how the kitchen will run, the more precisely a consultant can recommend models and quantities instead of generic suggestions."},{"question":"Can a consultant help me avoid buying the wrong equipment?","answer":"Yes, that is much of the value. A consultant flags mismatches like a fryer bank too small for your lunch rush or refrigeration that will not hold your prep, before you commit budget. Catching these on paper is far cheaper than discovering them during service, when fixes mean rush orders and downtime."},{"question":"Is equipment consulting only for new restaurants?","answer":"No. Existing kitchens use consulting when changing concepts, adding menu items, expanding volume, or replacing aging equipment. Any time a decision will affect throughput or capital cost meaningfully, a consultation helps you spend on the gear that actually moves the needle for your operation."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$equipment-consulting$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Equipment financing lets you acquire commercial kitchen gear without paying the full cost upfront, spreading payments over time so you can preserve working capital for inventory, staffing, and opening costs. For new and growing operators, financing can be the difference between equipping a kitchen properly and cutting corners on critical machines. Terms, rates, and approval depend on the provider and your business profile, so the right structure varies. Within this directory, financing is offered by Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"Why finance commercial kitchen equipment instead of paying cash?","answer":"Financing preserves cash you may need for inventory, staffing, marketing, and the unpredictable costs of opening or expanding. Spreading equipment cost over time keeps more working capital available when you need it most. Whether financing makes sense depends on your cash position and the terms offered, so weigh the cost of financing against the value of keeping cash on hand."},{"question":"Which supplier in the directory offers equipment financing?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply offers equipment financing and is the only supplier in this directory listing it, alongside equipment leasing. Because Shop at Stop also provides procurement, design, and consulting, you can potentially handle equipping and financing your kitchen through a single relationship rather than coordinating separate providers."},{"question":"What is the difference between financing and leasing equipment?","answer":"Financing generally means you are working toward owning the equipment, with payments structured around the purchase. Leasing is closer to paying for use over a term, often with options at the end. Which fits depends on whether you want to own the gear long term and how you want it treated for your books, so discuss both options with the provider."},{"question":"What do I need to qualify for equipment financing?","answer":"Requirements vary by provider and typically consider factors like your business and credit profile, time in operation, and the equipment involved. Rather than assume specific terms, ask the provider directly what documentation and qualifications they require. Having your business financials organized before you apply usually speeds the process."},{"question":"Can I finance a full kitchen, not just one machine?","answer":"Often yes, financing can cover a single piece or a complete equipment package, which is helpful when outfitting a new build. Because that depends on the provider and the total amount, confirm the scope when you request a quote. Pairing financing with procurement from the same supplier can simplify how the package is structured."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$equipment-financing$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Equipment leasing lets a kitchen pay for the use of commercial gear over a set term, often with lower upfront cost than buying outright and with end-of-term options to consider. Leasing can suit operators who want to conserve capital, keep equipment current, or test a concept before committing to ownership. The exact structure, term length, and end-of-lease choices depend on the provider and your situation. In this directory, equipment leasing is offered by Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"How does leasing commercial kitchen equipment work?","answer":"Leasing means you pay to use equipment over an agreed term rather than buying it outright, which keeps upfront costs lower. At the end of the term there are typically options such as continuing, upgrading, or purchasing, depending on the agreement. Because structures differ, read the term length and end-of-lease options carefully before signing."},{"question":"Should I lease or buy my kitchen equipment?","answer":"Leasing favors lower upfront cost, conserving capital, and flexibility, while buying favors long-term ownership and no ongoing payments once paid off. The right answer depends on your cash position, how long you plan to keep the equipment, and how you want it treated financially. Compare the total cost of each path over the realistic life of the gear."},{"question":"Which supplier in the directory offers equipment leasing?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply offers equipment leasing and is the only supplier in this directory that lists it, along with equipment financing. Since Shop at Stop also handles procurement, design, and consulting, you can potentially source and lease equipment through one relationship instead of juggling separate providers."},{"question":"What happens at the end of an equipment lease?","answer":"End-of-term options vary by agreement and can include returning the equipment, renewing, upgrading to newer gear, or purchasing it. Because these choices and any associated costs are set in the lease, confirm them before you sign so there are no surprises later. Ask the provider to walk you through each scenario in plain terms."},{"question":"Is leasing a good fit for a brand-new restaurant?","answer":"It can be, since leasing lowers the upfront cash needed to equip a kitchen, leaving more for inventory and opening costs. It also gives flexibility if you are still proving out a concept. The tradeoff is ongoing payments and the total cost over the term, so weigh that against your expected cash flow before deciding."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$equipment-leasing$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Installation services cover the physical setup of commercial kitchen equipment, including positioning, leveling, and coordinating the connections and clearances each unit needs to run safely. Proper installation protects your warranty, prevents premature failures, and keeps your kitchen aligned with code and the manufacturer's requirements. For heavy cooking lines, refrigeration, and ventilated equipment, professional installation is often the difference between a smooth opening and a delayed one. In this directory, installation services are provided by Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"Why use professional installation instead of installing equipment ourselves?","answer":"Professional installation ensures equipment is positioned, leveled, and connected to the manufacturer's specifications, which protects performance and often the warranty. Improper setup can cause early failures, safety issues, or code problems. For complex cooking, refrigeration, and ventilated units, professional installation reduces the risk of an expensive callback after you open."},{"question":"Which supplier in the directory offers installation services?","answer":"Russell Hendrix Foodservice Equipment lists installation services in this directory. Because Russell Hendrix also offers design and technical drawings plus procurement, you can potentially keep layout, supply, and installation coordinated under one supplier, which reduces the number of parties you manage during a build."},{"question":"Does installation affect my equipment warranty?","answer":"It can. Many manufacturers expect equipment to be installed to their specifications, and improper installation may affect warranty coverage. Using a qualified installer and keeping documentation of the work helps protect your warranty position. Confirm the manufacturer's installation requirements for each major unit before setup."},{"question":"Should installation be coordinated with design and procurement?","answer":"Yes. When layout drawings, equipment orders, and installation align, units arrive that fit the plan and connect where the utilities were run. Disconnecting these steps invites mismatches, like equipment that does not fit the space prepared for it. Coordinating them, ideally through suppliers that offer multiple services, keeps a build on schedule."},{"question":"When should installation be scheduled in a kitchen project?","answer":"Schedule installation once the space, utilities, and ventilation are ready and the equipment has arrived, and coordinate it with your construction timeline so trades are not waiting on each other. Rather than fix a date too early, align installation with confirmed delivery and site readiness. Building in some buffer accounts for lead times and inspection steps."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$installation-services$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Price match lets you confirm you are getting competitive pricing on commercial kitchen equipment by having a supplier meet a qualifying competitor quote. For operators watching margins, it removes some of the guesswork from shopping multiple vendors and can simplify a buying decision once you have found the model you want. Terms and what qualifies vary by supplier, so it pays to understand each policy. Several suppliers in this directory offer price match, which makes side-by-side comparison more straightforward.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"How does a price match policy actually work?","answer":"Typically you provide a qualifying competitor quote for the same equipment, and the supplier matches it under their stated conditions. The details, such as what counts as a valid competing offer and any documentation needed, vary by supplier. Because policies differ, ask exactly what qualifies before assuming a quote will be matched."},{"question":"Which suppliers in the directory offer price match?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply, Nella Cutlery and Food Equipment, Chefco, and Igloo Food Equipment all list price match. Shop at Stop ranks highest overall and pairs price match with a broad service range, so you can pursue competitive pricing while also accessing procurement, consulting, financing, and design under one supplier."},{"question":"Does price match guarantee the lowest possible price?","answer":"Not exactly. Price match means a supplier will meet a qualifying competitor quote, which keeps you competitive but depends on you finding and presenting that quote. It is a tool for confidence rather than an automatic discount. The accurate approach is to gather a few quotes first, then use the policy to close the gap."},{"question":"What information do I need to request a price match?","answer":"Generally you need a competitor quote that identifies the same equipment, ideally with model details and the price clearly stated. Requirements vary by supplier, so confirm what form of proof they accept. Keeping your competing quotes organized and current makes the request smoother and avoids back-and-forth."},{"question":"Is chasing a price match worth the effort for kitchen equipment?","answer":"On larger equipment purchases the savings can be meaningful, which makes it worthwhile to compare and request a match. On smaller items the effort may outweigh the difference. Weigh the potential saving against your time, and consider that factors like support, lead time, and warranty also affect total value beyond the sticker price."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$price-match$kd$;
update service_categories set description = $kd$Restaurant consulting goes beyond individual equipment decisions to look at how a foodservice operation comes together, from kitchen workflow and concept to the practical choices that affect daily service. It helps operators make better-informed decisions when opening, renovating, or rethinking how a kitchen runs. The value is in turning a vision into a workable plan grounded in real operational constraints. In this directory, restaurant consulting is offered by Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply, which also carries the widest overall service range.$kd$, faq = $kd$[{"question":"What does restaurant consulting cover?","answer":"Restaurant consulting takes a broader view than a single equipment purchase, looking at how your concept, kitchen workflow, and operational needs fit together. It helps connect decisions about layout, equipment, and process so they support the way you actually want to run service. The aim is a coherent plan rather than a series of disconnected choices."},{"question":"Which supplier in the directory offers restaurant consulting?","answer":"Shop at Stop Restaurant Supply offers restaurant consulting and is the only supplier in this directory listing it. Because Shop at Stop also provides equipment consulting, design and technical drawings, procurement, financing, and leasing, its restaurant consulting can tie directly into the practical steps of equipping and setting up the kitchen."},{"question":"How is restaurant consulting different from equipment consulting?","answer":"Equipment consulting focuses on choosing the right machines for your menu and volume, while restaurant consulting takes a wider view of how the operation works as a whole, including concept and workflow. The two complement each other: broader operational decisions shape what equipment you need, and equipment choices then support those decisions."},{"question":"When is the right time to bring in a restaurant consultant?","answer":"Early in a project, when you are shaping a concept, planning a new build, or rethinking an existing operation, is usually the most useful time. Decisions made early about workflow and layout are far cheaper to get right on paper than to correct after a kitchen is built. Engaging a consultant before major spending tends to pay off."},{"question":"Is restaurant consulting only for new openings?","answer":"No. Existing operators use it when renovating, changing concepts, expanding, or trying to fix workflow problems that slow service. Any time the way a kitchen runs is being meaningfully reconsidered, an outside operational perspective can help you avoid repeating costly mistakes and make the most of your space and equipment."}]$kd$::jsonb where slug = $kd$restaurant-consulting$kd$;
